And this taper is turning out beautifully in terms of healing. Didn’t even notice the temp... that may be a different story over in Chelan 😋. Rest of the week will be stat bike, travel, and a light hike.

MAAAAJOOORRR BONNK 😂😂😂
I didn’t realize how technical this singletrack would be after not being on this trail for more than a year. Super jagged  footing, gorgeous views, made for an awesome mostly-hike after a long week.
Everything is good, just more tired than usual. Cable Line -> Lake Serene  -> Road 10 miler was draining! May get a short run in later today.
Sweet way to spend an afternoon. Lumbering along home trails and exploring the MTB tracks for a few hours. Beautiful weather too!!!

I think pausing at the top probably caused the map mayhem. While I don’t mind believing I ran a 2:00” half mile, I think that is probably not true 😂. Wonder if I can kill the bad PRs while keeping the miles ??

I will probably set my pace in the race to the 2nd 5k to start and then hopefully chip away at times as the race goes on.

Pretty happy 😊

column3: PCT WA Section K out and back
column5:
A dear family friend recommended this trail to me about a week ago. It was said in full disclosure: this is known to be a difficult section of the PCT. But I would not be surprised if it is one of the most beautiful. 

I think I nearly died on roots more than 10 times. Overall a gorgeous day near home. No complaints

Great weather, great running, but no streams!!! Things felt super easy today. Would rather cut it while I feel good than grind through the full 50k without water. (And no I would not drink the lake water 😂)

column3: Lord Hill: Horse Trails -> Random Neighborhood
column5: Such a goofy route 😆. Definitely didn’t realize that the trail drained into a nice little neighborhood. Plenty of confused looks as I tried to navigate my way back to my car
Easy pace for a single loop at Wallace. The forest was really beautiful coming down.
Proper workout time was closer to 6 hrs. Pretty cool to have connected the bridges though 😊. Was not so fond of bonus miles at the end to round it out to a 50k 😬😬😬
Easy effort, working on footing and running efficiency. Got into a good groove and stayed there the whole time which is somewhat unusual for this route.
Again working on efficiency, footing, and getting in a bit of cardio. Great weather, now time for dinner with the fam 😊

Consistent pacing going up to the top of Teneriffe. Was surprised to see that the climb was mostly knocked out by 2:10. Would have liked to include blowdown, but didn’t feel like bushwhacking. Pretty solid training loop!!
Beautiful day with new friends! Trails were dialed and everybody was in good spirits.

column3: 90 min Power Zone Endurance Ride with Matt Wilpers
column5: 90 min Power Zone Endurance Ride from 4/27/19. Taken by wobmoonyos on Peloton.

Focused on efficiency and constant movement. Moderately difficult going up. No stops, no music, 1 transition (jacket), walking permitted only from bridge up to road grade. 

Had a big breakthrough running the upper grade. From the end of woody, constant running 😊

Also negative splits the whole way

column3: 90 min Power Zone Endurance Ride with Matt Wilpers
column5: Recovery ride, long easy miles Z2 and Z3
Strides felt very controlled, almost wished I had pushed harder at the end. HR and Breathing were steady nearly the whole time.
15 pct incline, 3-4 mph
Very chill and a great group. Definitely looking forward to the next  :)

Course distance was 40.53 mi, lap distance 1.93. Making the 40 mile goal was my primary reason for running this. The 9300 feet was mostly unplanned and dictated my pace for the majority of the day. 

Beautiful weather, great support and good spirits all enabled me to run within myself in a way that I haven’t experienced before. 

A wonderful day in Carkeek
Very mellow lord hill shakeout after Carkeek. Beautiful crisp day - felt a bit like winter. Had a PR at the entrance and sort of just plodded along after that.

Started pretty mellow and gradually worked up to something more like a race pace. Legs felt great, but they generally do with great company. Further evidence that running with your friends is both fun and helpful in training :)
Easy run tonight on mostly flat. Kind of satisfying to see my breath at night again 😊.

Today was a major test. I was 1.5 hr under cutoff at 28 mi. And had a pretty major slow down with nausea and perhaps a bit of dehydration. Ended up digging deep to make it to cutoff at mi 41. Slid under by 15-20 min. And gave my absolute hard effort the rest of the way. 

I won’t forget this experience any time soon. A beautiful day ...
Back in the swing of things. A bit tired, but that’s probably because I haven’t had coffee today 😂
Jog with Kelly was successful! We will see how far into this weekend workday I get before wanting a little nappy

column3: 30 min Power Zone Endurance Ride with Matt Wilpers
column5: 30 min Power Zone Endurance Ride from 11/15/19. Taken by wobmoonyos on Peloton.
Finally did the thing! Awesome group of people and great pacing on the run. Tons of fun 😊
Linked up with Nick T. for some vert at Wallace. So pretty at night!! Great conversation too, thanks dude
Mostly chill run with Kelly 😊. Got a bit cold at the end but most of the miles flew by. Perfect piece leading into weekend miles... not too fast, not too long. Feeling good
1 mi warmup, 4 mi track, 2 mi foot path

I like this run for a number of reasons: it is 99% on unobstructed bike path, the splits were almost totally negative, breath was just slightly short. 

I think the plan going forward with this block is to use this distance for a tempo on a semi regular basis. 

And if I can, I think it would be nice to hold to the paces in this run.
Chill flat 7 mi. Pace even at low exertion seems to be picking up. Feeling a little bit of fatigue already from this week. Just need to keep the joints and ligaments happy
Woke up at 3 am to run with a bunch of hooligans out in Japanese Gulch. Total blast, great company. I’ll be back here soon!!! #RWRUNSTREAK

Perfect conditions today: frost on the ground, not a cloud in the sky, and only a few people on the trail. Coming up on the end of week one of a new block. Tomorrow will be a long run but hopefully I’m able to dial it back to preserve some strength. Overall pretty content 😊

column3: Wallace: Woody-> Wallace Lake -> Jay Lake -> Greg Ball
column5: Long run with James. Great conversation as always 😊. Blowdown was dicey, but overall had a good time! Just a bit cold for sure 🥶🥶🥶

I really really like the climb on this trail. Steep but runnable.

My first lap of the day was mostly a hike, but second felt like it was mostly a run. I think if I were to go for pace, I might fall into 13:xx” range. 

This feels like it could be helpful for training for Chuckanut.
Focused on covering a medium run distance while expending minimal effort. This will be my last run before the weekend festivities with Nick Tyree and his 100 miler at Wallace.
Sometimes you have burps... sometimes you puke... sometimes they’re one and the same 🤷‍♂️. Still a mostly lovely weekday run. Flat and chill. Good base miles?

column3: Bridle Bogs, Bridle Fails, Bridle Slogs, Poopie Mudhole
column5: If you saw someone laughing at themselves covered in mud and horse shit, it very well could have been me. Such a blast. Bridle trails forever !!!!

column3: Seven Hills: Run Into the Lights
column5: To the family that had a narwhal decoration, and the other family a relief of donkey kong, I fully appreciated your efforts. 😍😍😍
Run with the Salomon buds. So much fun even with the tsunami in Grand Ridge 😊
Why avoid the puddle when you can stomp in it!?!?

column3: New trail up, old trail down!
column5: I kinda wished I hadn’t stopped moving. The climb on new trail is 👌. Maybe this could become a vert thing in my life 🤷‍♂️. Lotsa fun

I think I might need to race to find out what my actual PR is. For now, I’ll take the frequent improvements. Wouldn’t exactly call these past few months speedwork, but definitely pushing pace from time to time.

Thinking this is forming a decent boilerplate for the flat parts of Chuckanut 🤷‍♂️. Nice to have a bit of fitness before a big race...
Took the time to soak in some scenery. No PRs, just reveling in memories from a wonderful year. Very grateful  to have found this place.

I started running this loop at about 12:00 min/mile pace last year in April. The progression early on wasn't obvious. But after taking a break on this route, I'm finding that there was a pretty massive amount of gain in terms of pace somewhere in the last 6 months. Averaging 9:15 ish for this hill route is a big milestone, and a wonderful way to cap off the year.
Kept pace up on downhill. Thinking that these shorter high intensity runs may be helpful after all.
Moved fairly quick uphill. Ran consistently down. Felt solid and pretty easy the whole way through.

column3: A loop, a hill, and another loop 🤷‍♂️

column5: Because Grass Lawn...
Up was 42 ish. Down was mellow!
This was a loop that I didn’t even know existed. Impulsive, cold, and awesome 😎.
Muddy, miserable, awesome 😎. Pacing was a bit backwards but really satisfied with the result! Literally skiing in mud was a new trail experience.
The new hill route is in!! And it’s even got a wee bit of singletrack. In love with the new place, and the views are stunning from the run.
Basically Juanita to south Kirkland. So nice to have unobstructed sidewalks 👌. It makes exploring so much more fun!!!

Really wanted to run hard today but also needed to acknowledge the need to dial it back. No injuries or even pain, just looking at the block that I have coming up and trying to stay focused. Tomorrow is run club and a new demo 😊, and then onwards with Chuckanut block!!!
600 or so feet of gain and 10ish miles. Pretty ideal for a low impact base workout. Thinking I could probably spice it up a bit my running up to the connector trail on the way back.Solid
Short loop around one of the local trails. Pretty sure this can be connected to Big Finn, so perhaps I can get some miles in this coming week without too many loops.

So sunny!!! I can’t remember if I meant to run hard for this workout or not, but I was definitely inspired by the weather 😎. Half marathon went really well, and with a little refinement, could definitely see progress closer to the 1:50 mark.
Super fun little loop around big green lake and then down through lower woodland. WE GOTTA DO THE CC TRAIL!!!!
My 2 running groups converged and we had a running party (best kind of party)!! Speedy run in the demos and still feeling spry for a long run tomorrow :)
How in the world did we make 7.5 miles out of this!?! Such good company and a pretty damn solid run all things considered !!!
Time flew by with Aaron, Tiare, and Johnathan :). Very blessed to have great company on a perfect trail.

Feeling a bit more sore than usual but also was carrying about 10 lbs of gear to test out the BD distance 15 pack. Loving this thing through and through.

Run was mostly chill with a little bit of fast downhill. Nice way to cap off a productive week after working a Sunday !
Nice quick run without so much as a drizzle. Great turnout at ESR. Must admit I’m a bit hungrier for some vert after this run. We shall see where week 2 takes us ...

column3: Chuckanut 12 Out to Night W/Ginger Runner
column5:
There was a grand quote from TFA... it seemed relevant with ultra training “They come together and they fall apart.” 

Life isn’t always directed towards a solution but there is peace in knowing and acknowledging ebs and flows. 

Found the talks tonight to be wonderfully candid, and sometimes unresolved. Very happy I spent the time and money to go to this event.

Long week, deserved a relaxing hour outdoors. Happy with my progress so far through this block. Tough to say really if I am getting stronger due to fatigue. But my confidence is really improving day to day. 

I think a month of cleaning up my diet will also lead to some substantial improvement. For now just in a good space 😊

Always enjoy getting out on the trails with this dude ... even if I did only go for 1xloop 😋.

Great catching up man, won’t be the last time I make it out to Wallace before Chuckanut!!

column3: Chuckanut 15 Cable Line W/SarahRose and Emily
column5:
Chill Cable Line aka still equally strenuous cable line. Doggos, friends, snow, and sunshine. Feels like we might be out of the gloom for now!!!

Might go for an extra 5 tonight depending on how much I am enjoying the rest of my Sunday 😝

Struggled to get out the door, but made it just in time for sunset.

Sometimes having a mental tantrum sets the tone for an easy effort 😊. Super chill, epic views

On target for pace, needed more than .5L of water and a car key to make it through the full 30k of ridge running.

Great lead up to the “grinder hill” and chinscraper.

Also nice to know that a fall on the ridge is potentially fatal. That tumble would be no fun !
Group runs are so much more fun

column3: Chuckanut 22 Runnable Uphill W/Nick and Kelly
column5: Golly that was fun. Downhill was super satisfying until my headlamp died in front of a log 😂

column3: Chuckanut 24 Wallace with Tiare, Amy, and Raisin Bran 🤗
column5:
So pretty today. Took a little logging road detour. That was surprisingly sunny and then all the way down the Greg Ball trail, the ferns and moss were lit up by the sun. 

So grateful !!!

Just felt like I needed to get out and burn off some energy. Also wanted to explore the roads from Kirkland to Burke Gilman.

Decent pace, not too hard on the way out. Probably could have picked it up for the last 4 mi. 

Overall pretty happy with this road run.
Man I get it... pools are better. They are warm, and they keep you from feeling any impact at all. I even got my heart rate up. Quite stoked on this new Gym Perk :)

column3: Chuckanut 27 Clear Night at Bridle Trails
column5: Such a beautiful night out. Trails in perfect condition, not even a cloud. Pacing was good and the bonus miles were chill.

column3: Chuckanut 28: Speedy Park Run W/ Tiare!!!
column5: Man that flew by!!! So much fun stompin in the rain.
Super mellow. Unbelievable sunset over Mercer.

It’s only fitting that Chuckanut gets cancelled on the 30th workout of my block. Beautiful day outside with Brother and Frand in Juanita. Sun showing, trails in perfect condition, kind of nice to be able to just run and not think about a goal!!

Not going to try to replace Chuckanut with a different big effort. Now looking towards the summer races and long runs I have planned.

Capping mileage at 45-50/ week for about a month and a half until base runs feel really easy. Then I’ll maybe add in a bit of running economy. Hill work will go down twice a week to start.

Feeling strong and positive!

Damn. Of all the times I’ve ran this loop, this is the fastest. Not even by a small amount. 

Looking back on some of my first strava times, I think I started running this loop a few years ago around 11:30”/mi. 

Tangible progress l!

It felt so good and familiar. Every time my foot hit the pavement I knew where it would land. No guessing, and the hills felt strangely comfortable.

Thinking of the best way to avoid burnout with consistent volume. I really enjoy the connector trail, and taking a short detour through Bellevue is actually pretty pleasant.

Pretty quick workout too!
A man complemented me on my crotchlamp tonight. It filled me with joy... and simultaneously creeped me out. I’m still conflicted 😐

column3: Nothing is Wrong, Everything is Normal, Nothing to See Here: Zach and Jen edition
column5: A wonderful day but a bit on the crowded side given the circumstances.  Great company !!

Trying to maintain fitness and mental health is a bit of a paradox during quarantine. On the one end you have to get out for some amount of time and for your own purpose, but on the other, you’re responsible as a citizen to maintain distance ALL the time.

Hoping that these solo runs don’t appear childish or self centered. Otherwise spending all of my time alone at home.

Carrying 1 L

Hilly tempo 
Quarter mile fast and boardwalk coming back
Even with gear this felt easy. Starting to make friends with market street. A bit spooky without anybody around. Also kinda pleasant m
Too many people but everybody in good spirits
Kind of the perfect amount of fatigue and chill/alone time. This run is starting to feel more and more like a ritual. But asphalt is asphalt and concrete is still concrete ...
Spent some good time with Mom, Dad, and Chapo this weekend. Was definitely needed. Now going on taper for a long run next week so should be pretty mellow for the next few days.
This mug has nothing to do with tapering. I just like it a lot

Juanita Heights Park came through in a pinch ! Have to admit that it wasn’t as easy as I had planned. About 90% of the gain came from the same mile - steep! But single track is single track.


I think I might actually use this route again.

Firing on all cylinders after a day off. Starting to think compression sleeves actually work in recovery!

Usual Monroe-Home loop, a little spicier than intended at the end. 

Flirting with my recent PR suggests that road is still pretty goodish for my fitness. Now if I can just hold on till trails open up!!
Quick hill session! Felt comfortable the whole way through. Will definitely use this route again!!

column5: 45 min Power Zone Endurance Ride from 11/21/19. Taken by wobmoonyos on Peloton.

column5: 90 min Power Zone Endurance Ride from 3/23/19. Taken by wobmoonyos on Peloton.

column3: 90 min Power Zone Endurance Ride with Matt Wilpers
column5: 90 min Power Zone Endurance Ride from 1/4/20. Taken by wobmoonyos on Peloton.

Super chill trail run around lord hill. A fair amount of elevation, but not uncomfortable.

Knees are nice and loose. Still feeling strong! I think as I start to ramp up, a little light speedwork will definitely improve turnover and VO2 max. 

So for now the plan is to continue with stretching and maybe 2 light runs next week. 1@5 and 1@7.5.
Socially distant and not many ppl at the trailhead! Perfect weather. Leg healing up too. Overall great run with a friend!

Unreal weather on the other side of the mountains. Took it easy on the knee today and it turned out to be in very good shape. Downhill was a little steeper than I expected 😢. Come to think of it, so was the uphill😢😢. But couldn’t be happier to have gotten out and about!
Apparently I have a thing for running radio tower routes? Who knew!?
Mellowish vert session. Seemed like a pretty efficient workout
Slow as a sloth, but mighty at heart 😊

This was an awesome effort for a few reasons:
1. It felt comfortable 
2. The weather was perfect
3. Uphill game was mechanically efficient. I was happy to move pretty seamlessly between power hiking and running short steps. Never felt out of breath!!
Definitely took an unexpected detour to the land of stinging nettles. Literally ended up in a dead end full of them. Still a good run 😛

Perfect weather
Quiet meadows
Loud off-road vehicles 😡
Good water management !!!
Soft and flowy singletrack 👌

Today felt super strong especially given the larger effort this weekend. 

Run-Climbing is really coming together on this course. Not sure if that’s because I’m getting familiar with the trail or if I’m actually making progress.

Even though the PRs on individual segments don’t show it, most of the hills were ran. Feels good
It was so dang muggy today!!! Totally drenched after this workout. Maybe that’s good heat training?
I found another radio tower. It’s like 30 feet away from the other radio tower. Why you need two bro 🙄!?
Soft ground for the win! Easy day while gradually stepping up base mileage.
Really pleased with today’s climb efforts. Found a sustainable tempo and just kept at it. Downhill was a tad on the aggressive side. Probably should back off for future mid-week workouts 😬
Trying to take the “extra” miles as easy as possible. Was pretty straight forward until I got kicked off the track 🤷‍♂️. Win some lose some
Pretty happy with the climb on today’s run. Nice to have a hot run to kick off heat training for the summer. Downhill was Uber mellow. Even got to filter some stream water which lifted my spirits.

Ok... I get it. They prevent injuries, they’re great on tippy climbs, they save some strength for late in the game. BUT I HATE THEM. 

Also hot as balls out. 86 degrees and ungodly humidity. 

Lotta walkin... still a pretty good workout
My brown REI wool socks have finally given up the ghost. I’ve had them for 7 years and they’ve been on countless adventures and many many trail runs. Perhaps I should give them a proper burial 🧐?

column3: Oregon Cascades 100 Start -> AS1 and Back
column5: Literally the softest trail I have ever been on. The smell, the sounds, the sunrise... everything was perfect

column3: Exploring a TINY Chunk of Sisters
column5: Super moody weather today. Went from 75 to 42 and raining only as high desert could. Still gorgeous and quiet!
Absolutely gorgeous. Nice to have another dusty trail for the week. Did a bit of fishing recon as well
Another beautiful day on dusty riverside trails. Could definitely get used to this weather. Dry and warm !!!
Home loop with an extra little hill.
A nice little run/walk around home loop 🙂. Just cruised over the 1000 mile mark for the year. Also here is Chapo...
The birds were chirpin, the sun was setting, my audiobook (Dune) just getting interesting. Great start to the week

Completely gorgeous night out in white pass (Rainier). Moved very comfortably on the uphill and met John and Liz at about their mile 10 to help them finish a 28 mi segment.

Lots of factors made this otherwise runnable trail a bear at night: blowdown, climbing, mad temperature swings, variable water access.

Both of them handled it totally perfectly. Even when things got a bit hairy at the end and had to link up after getting a bit turned around in the last mi.

John, you’re a complete animal. Turned around after what sounded to be a heinous 70 mi push with minimal water access to full recovery mode, napping and then back out on course in a couple hours is unheard of.

Still processing the magnitude of his effort
